image.altText: Mitchell Starc holds his finger in the air and runs off yelling in delight

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: What an absolute seed from Mitchell Starc, angling towards outside off and swinging back down the line of middle stump late and right through the gate of Ollie Pope. Brilliant stuff for Australia.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BOWLED HIM! STARC RIPS POPE'S MIDDLE STUMP OUT OF THE GROUND!!

props.alt: Ollie Pope, seen from behind, as his middle stump is removed by a cricket ball during a Test.

children.content: What an absolute seed from Mitchell Starc, angling towards outside off and swinging back down the line of middle stump late and right through the gate of Ollie Pope.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Mitchell Starc swung one miles down leg and Crawley just chased it. Starc was adamant in his appeal and Crawley turned his back. Chris Gaffaney thought long and hard about it, but eventually the finger went up and Crawley didn't review. He knew he nicked it. Good grab by Alex Carey down the leg side. One down, nine to go for Australia.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ZAK CRAWLEY IS OUT!

props.alt: Mitchell Starc throws both hands up as he appeals for Zak Crawley's wicket.

children.content: Mitchell Starc swung one miles down leg and Crawley just chased it.

Starc was adamant in his appeal and Crawley turned his back. Chris Gaffaney thought long and hard about it, but eventually the finger went up and Crawley didn't review. He knew he nicked it. Good grab by Alex Carey down the leg side.
One down, nine to go for Australia.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: So, England will need to chase their highest ever score at Lord's and second highest of all time to win this second Test match. England did chase 378 against India just last year at Edgbaston, so will fancy themselves to do this with four sessions. Will that 15-run partnership make the difference between success and failure in this Test? Only time will tell, but that was a truly bizarre spectacle.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australia all out for 325, lead by 370

children.content: So, England will need to chase their highest ever score at Lord's and second highest of all time to win this second Test match.
England did chase 378 against India just last year at Edgbaston, so will fancy themselves to do this with four sessions.
